'''Symphony No. 1, Op. 13''' in E♭ by the [[Romania]]n composer [[George Enescu]] reflects the composer's training in both Vienna and Paris. In the former location he studied the Brahmsian tradition with [[Robert Fuchs]], and in the latter the French tradition with [[Jules Massenet]] and [[Gabriel Fauré]] {{harv|Botstein|n.d.}}.

==History==
Enescu completed the symphony in 1905 {{harv|Bentoiu|2010|loc=98}}, and it was premiered on Sunday, 21 January 1906 at the [[Théâtre du Châtelet]] in Paris, on the fourteenth concert of the 1905–06 series of the [[Concerts Colonne]], conducted by [[Édouard Colonne]] {{harv|Hoffman and Rațiu|1971|loc=311–12}}. It was published by Enoch et co., Paris, in 1906. The score is dedicated to [[Alfredo Casella]], Enescu's former classmate at the Paris Conservatoire and lifelong friend. In turn, Casella would dedicate his Second Symphony to Enescu in 1908 {{harv|Bentoiu|2010|loc=99}}.

==Instrumentation==
The symphony is scored for 3 flutes (third doubling piccolo), 2 oboes, cor anglais, E{{Music|flat}} clarinet, 2 clarinets, bass clarinet, 3 bassoons, contrabassoon, 4 horns, 2 trumpets, 2 cornets, 3 trombones, tuba, timpani, percussion (triangle, tambourine, cymbals, bass drum), 2 harps, 20 first violins, 18 or 20 second violins, 14 violas, 12 cellos, and 12 contrabasses.

==Analysis==
The symphony falls into three [[movement (music)|movements]]:
*Assez vif et rythmé
*Lent
*Vif et vigoureux
The first movement is dominated by the three component motives of the first theme, announced in unison at the beginning {{harv|Hoffman and Rațiu|1971|loc=306}}. It is in the traditional [[sonata form|sonata-allegro form]], with a rather short development section and the culmination in the [[Recapitulation (music)|recapitulation]] {{harv|Bentoiu|2010|loc=87–88}}.

The slow movement can be regarded as an extended ''[[Lied]]'' form: ''A–B–C–B–C–A'', preceded by an introduction and concluded with a coda. However, the second half (the ''B–C–A'' portion) does not simply repeat the material from the first part, but develops it, and is not followed with a full recapitulation but closes rather suddenly with only the ''A'' material, and then the coda {{harv|Bentoiu|2010|loc=88}}.

The exposition of the finale, also in sonata-allegro form, is similar to that of the first movement, with the main difference being that the place of a first theme is taken by a group of clearly defined thematic elements (the first, in the unison strings, forms a quasi-permanent background, followed by a second figure in the brass, a third in the trombone, and so on). The second theme is anticipated in triplets, only gradually achieving a stable profile after several attempts {{harv|Hoffman and Rațiu|1971|loc=307}}.

